T1  - Diversification, Systematic Risk, and Shareholder Return: A Capital Market Extension of Rumelt's 1974 Study
AU  - Lubatkin, Michael
AU  - Rogers, Ronald C.
Y1  - 1989/06/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256370
DO  - 10.5465/256370
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 454
EP  - 465
VL  - 32
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study reexamined the performance outcome of diversification strategies by combining the advantages of security-market-based measures and Rumelt's classification scheme. The findings underscore the popular, though weakly supported, belief that controlled diversity is associated with the highest performance. Specifically, firms that diversified in a constrained manner demonstrated significantly lower levels of systematic risk and significantly higher levels of shareholder returns than firms employing other strategies.
AB  - This study reexamined the performance outcome of diversification strategies by combining the advantages of security-market-based measures and Rumelt's classification scheme. The findings underscore the popular, though weakly supported, belief that controlled diversity is associated with the highest performance. Specifically, firms that diversified in a constrained manner demonstrated significantly lower levels of systematic risk and significantly higher levels of shareholder returns than firms employing other strategies.
